20
00:02:45.053 --> 00:02:51.053
So what's confidential computing? Very quickly, it has three pieces to it. Number one.


21
00:02:51.053 --> 00:03:03.053
You provide data in use protection by running your applications, your workloads in hardware-protected environments called trusted execution environments.


22
00:03:03.053 --> 00:03:14.053
Okay? Everything that runs in there. is encrypted, and it's in the control of the owner of that application workload data, whichever it is.


23
00:03:14.053 --> 00:03:27.053
Okay? And the third important property of confidential computing is… you're going to get what is called an attestation, which says this is exactly what the environment in which you are running it.


24
00:03:27.053 --> 00:03:31.053
It's going to tell you the hardware it is in.


25
00:03:31.053 --> 00:03:43.053
What's the firmware that's running there? What's the software that's running there? And if you are happy with it, that's when you interact with it, give it secrets, give it keys, all kinds of things.


26
00:03:43.053 --> 00:03:47.053
And why are we so interested in confidential computing?


27
00:03:47.053 --> 00:03:53.053
You can see on the right side of the picture there, it gives you some good protections.


28
00:03:53.053 --> 00:03:59.053
It gives you protections from day zeros to some degree.


29
00:03:59.053 --> 00:04:07.053
It protects you from the… administrators of your infrastructure, whether it's on-prem or in the cloud.


30
00:04:07.053 --> 00:04:14.053
It gives you protection from other tenants that are running on the same infrastructure.


31
00:04:14.053 --> 00:04:31.053
Okay? So confidential computing that way gives you the protection from the infrastructure on which your workloads are running. You don't need to worry about, hey, this cloud operator could get access to what I'm doing. This cloud operator could have a rogue administrator that.


32
00:04:31.053 --> 00:04:42.053
takes a snapshot of your virtual machine or your container, and they got all your secrets. All of those threat vectors disappear for the most part with confidential computing.


33
00:04:42.053 --> 00:04:55.053
And for AI workloads, that's why it's very important. It protects your models, it protects your data. If you're doing gen AI stuff, it protects your prompts, your context windows, all of that stuff.


34
00:04:55.053 --> 00:05:12.053
And I'm going to show you how, okay? There are two models for confidential AI. One is… running everything in confidential computing on CPUs, okay? I'm an Intel guy, so I have to talk about this use case, okay?


35
00:05:12.053 --> 00:05:16.053
It's good for inferencing, it's good for certain model sizes.


36
00:05:16.053 --> 00:05:25.053
